T1  - Solution and estimation of linear rational expectations models
AU  - Salemi, Michael K.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 31
IS  - 1
SP  - 41
EP  - 66
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/02/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(86)90055-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407686900552
AB  - This paper addresses the issue of solution and estimation of linear rational expectations models. It confirms, via the method of undetermined coefficients, the finding that these models do not, in general, imply unique solutions for the variables they explain. But it provides evidence in the form of a Monte Carlo experiment that one may recover accurate estimates of the parameters that characterize the solution set with which the data were generated. The estimation strategy proposed and implemented is FIML subject to the restrictions placed on the final form by the structural equations, the hypothesis of rational expectations, and the assumption of a stable multivariate moving average representation for the endogenous variables.
